woman presents with a one day history of right sided abdominal pain and nausea. She reports three similar episodes in the last month. Her blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, pulse rate 90/min and temperature 36.8\u02daC. There is tenderness in the right upper quadrant and the rest of the physical examination is normal. An abdominal ultrasound examination is performed (Image). Consideration is given to the use of antibiotics prior to any definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Expectant management","Antispasmodic therapy","Intravenous antibiotic therapy","Elective cholecystectomy","Emergency cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is consistent with an episode of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiliary colic.\u003C/strong\u003E There are no features of fever or leukocytosis, which would suggest acute cholecystitis. In addition, there are is no suggestion of jaundice making acute cholangitis and choledocholithiasis unlikely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients with typical biliary colic and gallstones on imaging who are surgical candidates, current guidelines recommend \u003Cstrong\u003Eelective cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E in order to prevent future attacks of biliary colic and complications of gallstone disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are no signs of complicated gall bladder disease including gangrene/necrosis, perforation, or emphysematous cholecystitis, so there is no indication for an \u003Cstrong\u003Eemergency cholecystectomy.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs there are no signs of an infectious process, \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntispasmodics\u003C/strong\u003E do not have a role in the treatment of biliary colic because they offer little analgesic benefit if co-administered with NSAIDs or opioids. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Elective cholecystectomy is the definitive management option for patients with typical biliary colic and gallstones on imaging, who are suitable surgical candidates","When a patient presents like this to the emergency department, ensure that their pain has settled before discharge, and advise them to return if symptoms worsen, as they may have presented early in the course of an episode of acute cholecystitis, in which case emergency cholecystectomy is the most effective treatment."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Biliary Colic. Therapeutic Guidelines. December 2020. Accessed September 22, 2022. https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Pain%20and%20Analgesia\u0026topicfile=biliary-colic\u0026guidelinename=Pain%20and%20Analgesia\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e170#toc_d1e170","Zakko S. Overview of gallstone disease in adults. Up to Date. Updated April 25, 2022. Accessed September 22, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-gallstone-disease-in-adults?search=biliary%20colic\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1Overview of gallstone disease in adultsOverview of gallstone disease in adults"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22810"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"783"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18776"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18776"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a844ca18-d353-4255-b29c-f14f2c8644e6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a844ca18-d353-4255-b29c-f14f2c8644e6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":516,"height":418}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/